What is Forecasting¶

Forecasting is predicting the future given all the information available which includes historical data and knowledge of any future events that might impact the forecast.

Examples of where forecasting is important:

- Short-term forecasting for scheduling employees, production and transportation.
- Medium-term forecasting for purchasing raw materials, hire personal, or buy machinery and equipment.
- Long-term forecasts for stategic planning.

Forecasting situation vary widely in their time horizons, factors detrmining actual outcome, types of data patterns, etc.

Types of forecasting methods are simple such as the naive method, which takes the most recent observation as a forecast, or complex methods such as neural nets. No matter what type of forecasting method is used complexity harms forecast accuracy by 25% [3]. So we need to choose the best forecasting method for our situation with as little complexity as possible to answer our questions.

Let us try an Example¶

We will go through the basic steps of a forecasting task as outlined by Rob J Hyndman:

  1. Problem Definition/ Overview:

    Define the problem and carefully decide the way the forecast will be used, who requires the forecast, and how the forecast function fits within the questions that are asked.

  1. Gathering Information:

    Gather the statistical data. Good statistical models will handle evolutionary changes in the system; don't throw away good data unnecessarily. This will also be the step of data preprocessing.

  1. Exploratory Data Analysis:

    Start by graphing the data and making note of any consistent patterns, significant trends, seasonality, outliers, and relationships between variables.

  1. Choosing and Fitting Models:

    Choosing a model depends on the availability of historical data, strength of relationships between variables, and the way the forecasts are to be used. It is common to compare two or three potential models using train and test sets.

  1. Using and Evaluating a Forecasting Model:

    Once a model is selected and its parameters estimated we can use the model to make forecasts. Then we will choose a method for assessing the accuracy of the forecast.

Overview of Problem¶

Quantitative Forecasting vs Qualitative Forecasting:¶

Qualitative forecasting is used when data is scarce. It uses human judgement and rating schemes to turn qualitative information into quantitative [4]. Some techniques include the Delphi method, Market research, or Panel Cansensus.

Quantitative Forecasting models: There are three types of models to describe quantitative forecasting.

  1. Explanatory Model assumes that the variable to be forecast exhibits an explanatory relationship with one of more other variables called predictor variables [2]. Using the example problem above, if we were trying to forecast the yearly bike usage of Nice Ride's bike program (BU), we might use predictor variables, temperature, time of day, and events in city, such that:

Explanatory Model Equation/ Causal Method

$BU = f(temperature, time of day, events in city, error)$

  1. Time Series Model uses only information on the variable to be forecast, bike usage (BU) just like in the case above, and makes no attempt to discover the factors affecting it's behavior [2]. Let it be the present time (hour, day, week) so:

Time Series Analysis Model Equation

$BU_{t+1} = f(BU_{t}, BU_{t-1}, ... , BU_{t-n}, error)$

  1. Mixed Model/Dynamic Regression Models uses both the explanatory model and the time series model. An equation for our example could be such that:

Dynamic Regression Model Equation

$BU_{t+1} = f(BU_t, current temperature, time of day, events in city, error)$

Example Problem¶

In 2010, Minneapolis and St. Paul became one of the nation's first cities to implement a bicycle-sharing program. It started with 700 bicycles and 65 stations [https://www.niceridemn.com/about]. Currently, there are 3000+ bikes and 400+ stations across the Twin Cities. Nice Ride bike share was designed for quick trips and convenience.

Bike shares are an interesting topic for us and we are interested in Nice Ride's future outlook and how they have done thus far. A few questions we are going to investigate are:

  1. What is the overall bike usage for each year and the predicted usage for future years?
  2. What is the typical duration of a trip? Should we change how we charge people, either per trip or by duration?
  3. What stations are the most frequent starting points for trips? Should we add more bikes at the frequent starting point or should we remove bikes at the frequent starting point?

The first question uses one variable to predict the future outlook. This would be an example of a Time Sereies Model. The time series variable used in the first question will be bike usage which we will define as any trip with any duration of time used.

The second question uses a mixed model or dynamic regression model.

The second question will use duration as the main variable for time series with the predictor variable being an outside variable cost. We will be using their cost outline found at https://www.niceridemn.com/pricing and the membership type/account type.

The third question will use one variable to predict the future outlook. This would be another example of a Time Series Model. The time series variable will be the frequency of start stations per day.

Data Preparation import from CSV files¶

The NiceRide bikeshare data was acquired from: https://www.niceridemn.com/system-data Visually exploring the csv files we can see there is:

Ride data attributes:

  • Start date
  • Start station
  • Start terminal
  • End date
  • End station
  • End terminal
  • Total duration (ms)
  • Account type
  • Bike Type (used when dockless bikes become available in 2018)

Because of the large dataset, we will reduce the number of variables during our data preprocessing.

We will keep the following variables

Ride data attributes:

  • Start date
  • Start station
  • End date
  • End station
  • Total duration (ms) or Total duration (sec) (change from ms to sec in 2015)
  • Account type
  • Bike Type (used when dockless bikes become available in 2018)

Some information about our csv files, when manually checking:¶

1) There are 32 csv_files, which:

  • 8 csv_files contain trips information from 2010-2017: ends with 'season.csv'
  • 8 csv files contain station information from 2010-2017: ends with 'locations.csv'
  • 16 csv files contain monthly trip information of year 2018 and year 2019: end with 'tripdata.csv'

2) Inconsistencies in column names in units in 8 csv_files (ends with 'season.csv') of trip information from 2010-2017

  • Total duration (ms): 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014
  • Total duration (Seconds): 2015, 2017
  • Total duration (seconds): 2016

Resolution: First, convert all values in 2010-2014 dataframe from ms to seconds. Then change all column name to 'Total duration (Seconds)'

3) Columns name change from 2018

  • Start date -> start_time
  • Start station -> start station name
  • End date ->end_time
  • End station -> end station name
  • Total duration (Seconds) -> trip duration (in seconds)
  • Account type -> usertype
  • NEW COLUMN: bike type (used when dockless bikes become available in 2018)

def list_files(path):
    csv_file = []
    pattern = "*.csv"

    for path, subdirs, files in os.walk(path):
        for name in files:
            if fnmatch(name, pattern):
                csv_file.append(os.path.join(path, name))
    return csv_file

my_csv_file=list_files('data/')

def check_columns(data_frame):
    col_namelist = []
    
    df = pd.read_csv(data_frame)
    for col in df.columns: 
        col_namelist.append(col)
    return col_namelist

# Note: Even though we have finished data preprocessing, we still stumble into one minor problem.

## Our final_data rarely has any data (from 2010-2019) for Date and Number of Biker from December-March ,
## When we run Time series, it is possible that we can misjudge our prediction,
## My resolution that we will store all our final_data into a dictionary (let's call it my_result)
## Then we will create a new list(let's call it full_date_list) range from 2010-06-01 to 2019-11-01 on daily frequency
## Then we will try to pattern matching our value in the list with keys in our stored dictionary.
## If there is a match, we will store both the keys and values of our stored dictionary into a NEW dictionary.
## If there is no match, we will use our values as the key, and values is zero:

## Example:
## my_dict = {'a':1,'b':2}
## my_list = [a,b,c]
## return: new_dict = {'a':1,'b':2,'c':0}
In [15]:
## Function to store a new dictionary

def convert_to_new_dict(my_dict,my_list):
    new_dict = {}
    for values in my_list:
        if values in my_dict.keys():
            new_dict[values]=my_dict[values]
        else:
            new_dict[values]= 0
    return new_dict

In [25]:
p = d = q = range(0, 2)
pdq = list(itertools.product(p, d, q))
seasonal_pdq = [(x[0], x[1], x[2], 12) for x in list(itertools.product(p, d, q))]

for param in pdq:
    for param_seasonal in seasonal_pdq:
        try:
            mod = sm.tsa.statespace.SARIMAX(y,order=param,seasonal_order=param_seasonal, enforce_stationarity=False,enforce_invertibility=False)
            results = mod.fit()
            print('ARIMA{}x{}12 - AIC:{}'.format(param,param_seasonal,results.aic))
        except:
            continue

Model¶

In [68]:
# Thresholds to remove outliers
minimum = 60           # 1 minute
maximum = 60 * 60 * 6  # 6 hours

# Partially mechanically determined and by hand
season_dates = {'2010':['2010-06-01', '2010-11-07'],
                '2011':['2011-04-07', '2011-11-06'],
                '2012':['2012-04-02', '2012-11-04'],
                '2013':['2013-04-03', '2013-11-03'],
                '2014':['2014-04-11', '2014-11-02'],
                '2015':['2015-04-01', '2015-11-01'],
                '2016':['2016-04-04', '2016-11-06'],
                '2017':['2017-04-03', '2017-11-05'],
                '2018':['2018-04-28', '2018-11-17'],
                '2019':['2019-04-28', '2019-11-17']}

def make_q2mod_df(df, resamp_freq, resamp_flag):
    temp = df.set_index('Date')

    # Remove outliers
    temp = temp[temp['Total duration (Seconds)'] >= minimum]
    temp = temp[temp['Total duration (Seconds)'] <= maximum]

    # Resample
    if resamp_flag:
        temp = temp['Total duration (Seconds)'].resample(resamp_freq).mean()
    else:
        temp = pd.Series(temp['Total duration (Seconds)'])

    # Remove weird data from before seasons' start and after thier end
    ts = pd.Series()
    for key in season_dates:
        mask = (temp.index >= season_dates[key][0]) & (temp.index <= season_dates[key][1])
        ts = ts.append(temp.loc[mask])

    return pd.DataFrame({'ds':ts.index, 'y':ts}).reset_index().drop('index', axis = 1).dropna(0)

# Create the training and test sets, and resample
q2mod_df_train = make_q2mod_df(q2_train, 'D', True)
q2mod_df_test = make_q2mod_df(q2_test, 'D', True)

Nice Ride Pricing Plans¶

Referencing Nice Rides website at https://www.niceridemn.com/pricing, their plans are as follows:

  • Single rides, up to 30 minutes \$2 per trip
  • Day Pass, unlimited 30-minute rides in a 24-hour period \$6 per day
  • Annual membership, unlimited 60-minute rides for 365 days \$75 per year

Question 2 Conclusion¶

Our forecast shows the average rider is not increasing their duration past the 30-minute limit. There are 2 days where this average duration exceeds the 30-minute limit. From the above table, they appear to be in the prime summer months. The Day Pass seems to be an excellent value for the customer during those days and would be the equivalent of three Single ride passes. The Annual membership equates to 37.5 Single passes or 12.5 Day passes. Nice Ride could see an increase in revenue, but at the possible expense of customer goodwill. Given Nice Ride's historical data and the assumption that their business model is promoting their goals, mission, and values we see no indication that they should change their pricing plan.

As we can see, if Nice Ride were to charge by trip duration, they would not generate any revenue. So, THEY SHOULD ALWAYS CHARGE PEOPLE PER TRIPS.

Nice Ride should keep how they currently charge people:

  • Single Ride
  • Day Pass
  • Annual Membership

Question 3 Conclusion¶

Let us review the question:

What stations are the most frequent starting points for trips? Should we add more bikes at the frequent starting point or should we remove bikes in at the frequent starting point?

We have created the trends for all four locations: IDS Center, 100 Main Street SE, Lake Street & Knox Ave S, YWCA Downtown.

IDS Center: The IDS nice ride station is most popular during the weekdays due to the location in downtown and is in use yearly from around May - November. The trend has been going downwards since 2015. We can see that in 2019 the number of rides started at this location is at 0. The reason being that NiceRide removed this location at the beginning of 2019. But why would they remove their most popular station? Obviously, it has been showing a decreaseing trend since 2015. I am going to guess the removal is due to the electic scooters which came to downtown Minneapolis in 2018. Which is around the time that dockless bikes also started.

100 Main Street SE: The 100 Main Street SE station is most popular on the weekends from May to November. Since around 2016 the trend has been pointed downwards. The location is between downtown and the University of Minnesota next to the Stone Arch Bridge. The nice ride station is still available but I am going to guess the decreasing trend is again due to the start of electric scooters and dockless bikes.

Lake Street & Knox Ave S: The station is most popular on weekends from April to October. The location is near Bde Maka Ska. The trend is decreasing but is still relatively high. Still averaging around 30 rides a day during the 2020 season. The success of this location is due to the close proximity to the lakes. Dockless may not be the best implementation of NiceRide near the lake since they can be placed in any location and may be hard to find for family and friend rides around the lake. Electric scooters are usually kept closer to downtown and uptown area.

YWCA Downtown: The station is most popular starting Thursday through Saturday night from May to October. The location is in downtown Minneapolis. The trend is slightly decreasing around 10 rides a day going into 2020. Since this location is in downtown I assume the decrease is, in part, due to the arrival of electric scooters and dockless bikes which are popular in downtown.

Conclusion¶

Now we are able to answer our question:

1.) What is the overall bike usage for each year and the predicted usage for future years?

We will used our FB Prophet to answer this question:

  • For each year, the services is only popular during April to October. This is understandable as Winter in Minnesota can affect the usage of biker.
  • If not account for current COVID-19, Nice Ride Minnesota still decreases in riderships (from 2018 to 2019), the real data shows that riderships has already decreased
  • In the near future, this services will not be in high demand, Unless there is a change in technology or company vision, this service might be failing to achieve its goals.

2.) What is the typical duration of the trip? Should we change how we charge people, either per trip or by duration?

As we can see, if Nice Ride were to charge by trip duration, they would not generate any revenue. So, THEY SHOULD ALWAYS CHARGE PEOPLE PER TRIPS.

Nice Ride should keep how they currently charge people:

  • Single Ride
  • Day Pass
  • Annual Membership

3.) Should we add more bikes to any of these locations?

With the trends found at each of these four locations from FB Prophet it suggests

  • We should not add more bikes and maybe even shift more into dockless bikes or electric bikes in the downtown areas.
  • The station close to Bde Maka Ska is a different situation. The data suggests that the station is doing well with around 30 rides a day during the season.

More research needs to be done to implement more dockless bikes in the area.
